patients are overrepresented in the cachectic clusters, but they occur

984
00:58:37.756 --> 00:58:41.436
across the three groups. So this is not a single cancer site

985
00:58:41.576 --> 00:58:42.135
phenomenon.

986
00:58:43.796 --> 00:58:47.716
So aside from very low self-reported physical activity, that's at the

987
00:58:47.736 --> 00:58:51.376
bottom there. So you can see that both the red and the orange group have higher

988
00:58:51.456 --> 00:58:54.896
rates of low activity as compared to the non-cachectic folks.

989
00:58:55.416 --> 00:58:58.756
The orange group looks better even than the control on

990
00:58:58.766 --> 00:59:02.656
every patient-reported outcome, whereas the red group, the

991
00:59:02.696 --> 00:59:06.496
high symptom burden group, you can see they look quite a bit worse than

992
00:59:06.536 --> 00:59:08.296
the control that's not losing weight.

993
00:59:08.366 --> 00:59:12.196
So anorexia and cachexia symptoms are 39% higher

994
00:59:12.616 --> 00:59:14.796
abnormal rates in the high symptom burden group.

995
00:59:17.456 --> 00:59:21.336
When you move on to looking at these groups biochemically, what you can see

996
00:59:21.376 --> 00:59:25.296
is that both cachexia groups have a high prevalence of abnormal liver markers,

997
00:59:25.476 --> 00:59:26.956
elevated cortisol and leptin.

998
00:59:28.636 --> 00:59:31.896
Sorry, low leptin, low albumin, and lower HDL-C,

999
00:59:32.376 --> 00:59:35.076
so kind of the profile you might expect with weight loss.

1000
00:59:35.656 --> 00:59:39.476
But when you zoom in on the stress and inflammation markers,

1001
00:59:40.116 --> 00:59:44.076
it's really clear, I think, that the high symptom burden group

1002
00:59:44.136 --> 00:59:47.346
in red has much profoundly higher levels of

1003
00:59:47.376 --> 00:59:51.296
these more cachexia-relevant markers than does the low symptom

1004
00:59:51.376 --> 00:59:51.996
burden group.

1005
00:59:52.816 --> 00:59:56.786
So perhaps it's these mediators that in part are associated with or

1006
00:59:56.856 --> 01:00:00.136
drive the symptom burden or can at least predict it.

1007
01:00:01.756 --> 01:00:05.476
So this is prognostic as well. Despite

1008
01:00:05.536 --> 01:00:09.356
having similar weight loss at baseline in the low symptom

1009
01:00:09.476 --> 01:00:13.246
group, the high symptom group in red goes on to lose more

1010
01:00:13.276 --> 01:00:17.056
weight a lot faster and to have lower survival.

1011
01:00:17.136 --> 01:00:20.996
So that's distinct from the lower symptom burden group in the yellowy orange

1012
01:00:21.096 --> 01:00:24.876
that really can't be distinguished from the green no active cachexia baseline

1013
01:00:24.956 --> 01:00:28.656
group for quite a long time, almost 10 or 12 months into

1014
01:00:28.696 --> 01:00:32.452
follow-up.What we don't know, though, is are these

1015
01:00:32.472 --> 01:00:36.212
different stages of cachexia, are these symptoms

1016
01:00:36.232 --> 01:00:40.012
early signals that truly identified patients that might benefit from

1017
01:00:40.152 --> 01:00:43.202
specific interventions or specific timing of intervention?

1018
01:00:43.772 --> 01:00:47.302
And we're hoping to learn that in partnership with our pre-clinical colleagues as

1019
01:00:47.312 --> 01:00:48.222
part of the grand challenge.

1020
01:00:51.132 --> 01:00:52.742
So to wrap up,

1021
01:00:53.732 --> 01:00:57.192
cachexia is a dynamic and potentially reversible process.

1022
01:00:57.212 --> 01:01:00.682
When we move beyond this kind of static 5% weight loss cutoff,

1023
01:01:01.212 --> 01:01:04.752
we find discrete episodes of cachectic weight loss that

1024
01:01:04.792 --> 01:01:05.382
resolve,

1025
01:01:06.272 --> 01:01:09.841
and they also recur, and that can allow us to better

1026
01:01:09.952 --> 01:01:13.772
study different subtypes and hone in on the right time period in the

1027
01:01:13.792 --> 01:01:17.341
clinical timeline. When we do that, we see that we have

1028
01:01:17.372 --> 01:01:20.792
clusters of patients that are distinguished by body composition as well as

1029
01:01:20.812 --> 01:01:24.672
symptoms, and that parses groups with differing rates of future

1030
01:01:24.732 --> 01:01:28.492
weight loss as well as differing survival, and to some

1031
01:01:28.532 --> 01:01:31.672
extent, differing biochemical profiles.

1032
01:01:31.702 --> 01:01:35.572
And then importantly, you find these clusters even in patients who are not

1033
01:01:35.612 --> 01:01:36.672
yet losing weight.

1034
01:01:38.792 --> 01:01:42.772
Finally, I hope you've been introduced to the large prospective study that we're

1035
01:01:42.812 --> 01:01:46.042
assembling that we hope will provide a new longitudinal

1036
01:01:46.092 --> 01:01:49.882
resource to find these subtypes and

1037
01:01:49.912 --> 01:01:52.912
work towards early models of prediction of cachexia.

1038
01:01:54.452 --> 01:01:57.832
So this is obviously a team effort, so I want to thank my co-lead

1039
01:01:57.872 --> 01:02:01.172
at my site, Betty Kahn, as well as the CanKen leadership.

1040
01:02:02.432 --> 01:02:06.132
And then I have a shameless plug. If you want to talk more about this, I will be

1041
01:02:06.172 --> 01:02:09.372
babysitting my post-doc Anlin Cao's poster on Wednesday

1042
01:02:09.412 --> 01:02:13.352
morning, and so we can talk both about cachexia as well as about how visceral

1043
01:02:13.372 --> 01:02:17.302
adiposity and age shape the tumor microenvironment in non-metastatic

1044
01:02:17.352 --> 01:02:19.132
breast cancer. So thank you very much.

1045
01:02:29.332 --> 01:02:32.952
Hi. Really fantastic talk. I have two questions that are

1046
01:02:32.972 --> 01:02:36.472
somewhat related maybe. One is you kind

1047
01:02:36.532 --> 01:02:39.191
of distinguish between these five

1048
01:02:40.371 --> 01:02:43.142
clusters that cachectic patients go through.

1049
01:02:43.142 --> 01:02:47.092
So I'm just wondering, is the idea that it's always dynamic that patients

1050
01:02:47.132 --> 01:02:50.972
are going to undergo moderate wasting and severe

1051
01:02:51.032 --> 01:02:54.441
wasting and/or splenomegaly at some point,

1052
01:02:54.852 --> 01:02:58.632
or can it be static and it varies between the patients?

1053
01:02:58.692 --> 01:03:01.532
And also my second question is basically,

1054
01:03:02.812 --> 01:03:04.812
are these clusters mutually exclusive?

1055
01:03:05.092 --> 01:03:08.532
So can a patient have splenomegaly and also severe wasting?

1056
01:03:09.572 --> 01:03:09.892
Yes.

1057
01:03:11.272 --> 01:03:14.932
So, first of all, I want to say we're early in this, so we haven't

1058
01:03:14.972 --> 01:03:17.932
completed all of the detailed analyses that we wish to do.

1059
01:03:18.552 --> 01:03:22.472
But we do see overlap between-- If you imagine the heat

1060
01:03:22.552 --> 01:03:26.152
map, there were patients in what we called the

1061
01:03:26.172 --> 01:03:28.852
splenomegaly group who were experiencing wasting

1062
01:03:28.912 --> 01:03:32.752
and also getting bigger livers or smaller

1063
01:03:32.762 --> 01:03:35.432
livers. So there was a lot of heterogeneity in that group.

1064
01:03:35.772 --> 01:03:39.572
The boundaries are not distinct, and there's lots of other ways, I think, to look

1065
01:03:39.592 --> 01:03:43.422
at those data. I think the earlier part of your question was driving at,

1066
01:03:44.972 --> 01:03:48.792
do patients, as they experience recurrent weight loss, cycle in and

1067
01:03:48.872 --> 01:03:52.432
out of these phenotypes? And I don't have a good answer to that yet, but we are

1068
01:03:52.472 --> 01:03:55.962
collecting the data to do that. We started with just

1069
01:03:56.632 --> 01:04:00.452
looking at change between two time points because

1070
01:04:00.492 --> 01:04:03.572
we're still segmenting the scans and quality controlling them.

1071
01:04:03.592 --> 01:04:07.432
But the hope is that we'll have repeated episodes and

1072
01:04:07.472 --> 01:04:11.092
repeated scans so that we can answer that question of, what does the

1073
01:04:11.132 --> 01:04:13.352
rebound look like? It's probably not till baseline.

1074
01:04:16.692 --> 01:04:17.812
Really impressive talk.

1075
01:04:19.352 --> 01:04:22.072
Amazing number of data points that you have.

1076
01:04:22.532 --> 01:04:23.832
I was trying to understand

1077
01:04:24.772 --> 01:04:26.032
when you showed us the

1078
01:04:27.892 --> 01:04:31.872
different groups, so patients that have stress, anxiety,

1079
01:04:33.692 --> 01:04:36.112
can you uncouple that from the weight loss?

1080
01:04:36.512 --> 01:04:40.432
So when you showed the survival curve, those patients had

1081
01:04:40.452 --> 01:04:43.672
the anxiety, the stress, the weight loss, but we already know that weight loss will

1082
01:04:43.752 --> 01:04:44.992
predict survival. So

1083
01:04:45.812 --> 01:04:49.072
is that possible to uncouple that so we're just looking at those

1084
01:04:49.092 --> 01:04:51.132
phenotypes without the weight loss-

1085
01:04:51.252 --> 01:04:51.332
Yeah

1086
01:04:51.342 --> 01:04:55.052
... to see if that's sufficient to drive the difference in survival?

1087
01:04:55.492 --> 01:04:56.352
That's a great question.

1088
01:04:56.382 --> 01:04:56.972
Does that question make sense?

1089
01:04:57.052 --> 01:04:57.592
I think so.

1090
01:04:57.712 --> 01:04:57.722
Yeah.

1091
01:04:57.772 --> 01:05:00.972
I can tell you how we've tried to evaluate that because we've thought about that.

1092
01:05:01.412 --> 01:05:01.812
One is,

1093
01:05:03.932 --> 01:05:07.702
unlike in a pre-clinical model where you know exactly when cancer initiation is,

1094
01:05:08.292 --> 01:05:12.172
we're seeing patients at diagnosis, which is variable time points

1095
01:05:12.212 --> 01:05:15.212
from cancer initiation, and many patients, as you know, have experienced weight

1096
01:05:15.252 --> 01:05:17.072
loss prior to their diagnosis, right?

1097
01:05:17.572 --> 01:05:17.652
So

1098
01:05:18.692 --> 01:05:22.452
our approach has been is we want to catch you in the red window, and we can tell

1099
01:05:22.512 --> 01:05:26.372
that, but how deep you are into that window is going to vary

1100
01:05:26.412 --> 01:05:30.172
on the individual level. So what I was worried about is, is the higher symptom

1101
01:05:30.272 --> 01:05:33.962
group just people who have lost more weight who have been in the red window longer?

1102
01:05:33.972 --> 01:05:37.832
And the answer is actually no. The duration of exposure to

1103
01:05:37.852 --> 01:05:41.632
cachectic weight loss, how deep are you in the red, is very similar.

1104
01:05:41.652 --> 01:05:45.372
Both the achieved weight loss and the weeks of exposure to weight loss are

1105
01:05:45.472 --> 01:05:49.172
very similar between the high and the low symptom burden groups, and yet their

1106
01:05:49.192 --> 01:05:53.152
destinies differ. So the red group loses more weight after that

1107
01:05:53.192 --> 01:05:55.312
baseline visit where we're measuring their symptoms

1108
01:05:56.352 --> 01:05:57.372
than the orange group.

1109
01:05:58.652 --> 01:06:02.532
So I think that what that tells us is there's an uncoupling then of the

1110
01:06:02.792 --> 01:06:06.262
weight loss that you've experienced until the time of that symptom assessment and

1111
01:06:06.292 --> 01:06:09.972
then where you go next. The red group loses weight faster and has shorter

1112
01:06:09.992 --> 01:06:13.722
survival. The orange group has much longer survival, and they lose weight,

1113
01:06:13.872 --> 01:06:17.432
but at a much slower pace thereafter. So I thought that was profound.

1114
01:06:17.472 --> 01:06:21.232
The other way we've tried to measure it is just simply doing some Cox modeling

1115
01:06:21.272 --> 01:06:25.172
where we try to look at how the symptoms predict survival and

1116
01:06:25.252 --> 01:06:26.312
subsequent weight loss,

1117
01:06:27.192 --> 01:06:30.292
controlling for the weight loss that's been achieved, so similar.

1118
01:06:30.392 --> 01:06:33.432
And again, the symptoms really do tell you who's at risk.

1119
01:06:33.512 --> 01:06:37.312
So turns out asking people how they feel is a powerful tool, which I

1120
01:06:37.332 --> 01:06:38.792
think many oncologists would tell you.

1121
01:06:39.452 --> 01:06:40.092
Great. Thank you.

1122
01:06:44.536 --> 01:06:48.056
Hi. I think you showed that patients with cachexia have low levels of

1123
01:06:48.216 --> 01:06:51.786
HDL or can have lower levels. So does that mean that

1124
01:06:51.816 --> 01:06:55.176
patients with dyslipidemia are more at risk for cachexia?

1125
01:06:56.916 --> 01:06:59.496
I don't know the answer to that question, but I think it's a good one.

1126
01:07:00.156 --> 01:07:01.716
Maybe you should ask it again in the panel.

1127
01:07:02.256 --> 01:07:03.216
Okay. Thank you.

1128
01:07:18.796 --> 01:07:22.776
Thank you very much. I just want to congratulate all the people who've gone

1129
01:07:22.816 --> 01:07:26.716
before me. I've recently introduced Mike Wickler at the in-house

1130
01:07:26.796 --> 01:07:30.456
seminar in Cold Spring Harbor, and he made an important point that the best

1131
01:07:30.496 --> 01:07:34.356
scientists are those who have imagination

1132
01:07:34.436 --> 01:07:38.136
and who are rigorous, and of course, you know that those two things are slightly at

1133
01:07:38.185 --> 01:07:40.876
odds. But I hope you've seen that as

1134
01:07:41.856 --> 01:07:45.376
this sort of field of cachexia is growing, there's a real

1135
01:07:45.416 --> 01:07:49.236
opportunity to have imagination because it touches on

1136
01:07:49.316 --> 01:07:53.276
so many aspects, and if you then study it rigorously, it takes you down so

1137
01:07:53.376 --> 01:07:56.986
many potential avenues of not only understanding a condition that

1138
01:07:57.096 --> 01:08:01.016
affects many patients, but also on understanding fundamental

1139
01:08:01.076 --> 01:08:05.016
principles of biology that are transferable to so many other conditions even

1140
01:08:05.056 --> 01:08:08.736
beyond cancer. And, as such, I would like to

1141
01:08:09.036 --> 01:08:12.756
invite all of you to think about studying the whole body response to

1142
01:08:12.796 --> 01:08:16.637
cancer and thereby contributing to this field that is growing of

1143
01:08:16.696 --> 01:08:20.297
understanding the biology of the human

1144
01:08:20.376 --> 01:08:20.916
condition.

1145
01:08:22.476 --> 01:08:24.016
I have no disclosures. I

1146
01:08:24.896 --> 01:08:27.656
want to follow on from what we've heard before.

1147
01:08:27.797 --> 01:08:31.556
It's easy to think about cachexia as a systemic disease from

1148
01:08:31.677 --> 01:08:35.217
tumor-mediated factors, and that's what we also do in our lab.

1149
01:08:35.276 --> 01:08:39.116
We are thinking about what cells within the microenvironment make which factors

1150
01:08:39.137 --> 01:08:42.717
that radiate out into the system, and which parts of the organ

1151
01:08:43.177 --> 01:08:46.956
orchestration can be affected through these factors, and then how do these networks

1152
01:08:46.996 --> 01:08:50.717
interact. And I've got a terrific team making contributions for it.

1153
01:08:50.816 --> 01:08:54.736
And I actually have also a terrific team represented here in

1154
01:08:54.776 --> 01:08:58.656
the audience, and I'm giving a shout-out here for their posters.

1155
01:08:58.717 --> 01:09:01.456
Go and see them and speak to them about their findings.

1156
01:09:01.736 --> 01:09:05.696
Amanda has a great set of results relating to how the tumor can be

1157
01:09:05.757 --> 01:09:08.797
targeted without affecting the host with a creative new idea.

1158
01:09:09.456 --> 01:09:12.116
Tubha has some great data showing how

1159
01:09:13.177 --> 01:09:17.076
hypercalcemia can drive terminal cardiac dysfunction and contribute to the

1160
01:09:17.156 --> 01:09:19.337
actual mechanism of death from cachexia.

1161
01:09:19.726 --> 01:09:23.536
And Alice has spent several years now studying healing from

1162
01:09:23.576 --> 01:09:26.016
cachexia and what molecular drivers might

1163
01:09:26.976 --> 01:09:30.797
enable recovery as organisms

1164
01:09:30.876 --> 01:09:33.637
come through the process of cachexia, and please visit their posters and have a

1165
01:09:33.656 --> 01:09:34.056
look at it.

1166
01:09:34.976 --> 01:09:38.837
I want to take a step back from the perspective of cachexia to say,

1167
01:09:38.916 --> 01:09:42.757
okay, what are the potential evolutionary underlying principles as

1168
01:09:42.896 --> 01:09:46.846
the whole organism responds to a perturbation response?

1169
01:09:47.156 --> 01:09:47.456
And I want

1170
01:09:48.356 --> 01:09:50.156
you to think about two potential scenarios.

1171
01:09:50.226 --> 01:09:54.217
One is that a tumor is immunogenic and the immune response is

1172
01:09:54.257 --> 01:09:58.236
sufficient to eliminate the tumor even very early on, and so the organism

1173
01:09:58.316 --> 01:10:02.096
goes through this transient state before then completely recovers, but

1174
01:10:02.116 --> 01:10:05.936
maybe have a small demarcation of having been exposed to a cancer, maybe even

1175
01:10:05.996 --> 01:10:09.936
unbeknown to the organism. And then there is a second scenario where

1176
01:10:09.946 --> 01:10:13.676
the initial activation of the immune system is insufficient, and a

1177
01:10:14.236 --> 01:10:17.316
chronic inflammation occurs and drives

1178
01:10:18.176 --> 01:10:22.046
progression of the organism ultimately to dying, and this is probably what

1179
01:10:22.096 --> 01:10:23.876
we call cancer-associated cachexia.

1180
01:10:24.216 --> 01:10:27.196
And I've split my talk into two sections here.

1181
01:10:27.256 --> 01:10:31.176
I'm trying to get you to understand that these two scenarios are not at

1182
01:10:31.216 --> 01:10:35.076
odds, but that they are actually having a unifying process, and I want you

1183
01:10:35.116 --> 01:10:39.076
to think about cachexia more in the context of paraneoplasia as

1184
01:10:39.136 --> 01:10:41.696
a whole as I go through these two examples.

1185
01:10:42.056 --> 01:10:45.616
And for the first example, I'd like you to think about what might be the

1186
01:10:45.696 --> 01:10:49.376
antigens here. You hear a lot about neoantigens in different talks at AACR,

1187
01:10:49.736 --> 01:10:52.976
and I'm not disputing that they are relevant, but there's also through

1188
01:10:53.016 --> 01:10:56.836
transcription of dysregulations in cancer cells, the expression of non-mutant self

1189
01:10:56.876 --> 01:10:59.876
that can be immunogenic, including onco-neural antigens.

1190
01:10:59.906 --> 01:11:03.815
And the first paraneoplasia study that I want you to think about is related

1191
01:11:03.856 --> 01:11:04.216
to that.

1192
01:11:05.116 --> 01:11:08.656
Specifically, if you look into tumors of patients with cancer, these are

1193
01:11:08.696 --> 01:11:12.256
patients with triple-negative breast cancer, and look at their expression

1194
01:11:12.316 --> 01:11:16.176
profiling by RNA-seq or protein expression, you see expression of

1195
01:11:16.696 --> 01:11:18.546
onco-neural antigens. In particular,

1196
01:11:19.396 --> 01:11:23.366
for example, here gene expression in cancer cells of-- I don't

1197
01:11:23.396 --> 01:11:24.926
know, can you-- Oh, yeah, you see the marker.

1198
01:11:25.416 --> 01:11:25.976
Of

1199
01:11:26.876 --> 01:11:29.916
genes that drive subunit productions of NMDA receptors.

1200
01:11:29.936 --> 01:11:31.756
That's a heterotetrameric

1201
01:11:32.616 --> 01:11:36.446
neurotransmitter receptor that is usually expressed in the brain exclusively and in

1202
01:11:36.456 --> 01:11:40.096
the developing brain. And actually, this subunit, GRIN2B, is one of the

1203
01:11:40.106 --> 01:11:42.466
subunits that's really only expressed during development.

1204
01:11:42.516 --> 01:11:46.266
In other words, it's not expressed in the adult organism, and it's also not

1205
01:11:46.296 --> 01:11:50.236
expressed in the thymus, so there's no priming for adaptive immunity to

1206
01:11:50.296 --> 01:11:54.036
this subunit. You can see that we can see this by RNA and by protein

1207
01:11:54.096 --> 01:11:56.396
expression, as you can see here within the tumors.

1208
01:11:57.656 --> 01:12:01.376
That can be immunogenic. And for example, you can follow titers of

1209
01:12:01.436 --> 01:12:04.806
antibodies against these proteins in patients with triple-negative breast cancer

1210
01:12:04.816 --> 01:12:08.696
and detect that they are elevated in the cohort of

1211
01:12:08.716 --> 01:12:12.196
cancer patients. Even in the healthy controls, we occasionally see some antibodies

1212
01:12:12.276 --> 01:12:15.516
against these proteins. And you can see that the expression of high

1213
01:12:15.576 --> 01:12:18.956
antibodies actually demarcates better outcome for these patients.

1214
01:12:18.996 --> 01:12:22.696
And again, when you look in the tumors, you can see there's protein expression in

1215
01:12:22.736 --> 01:12:24.976
the tumor of these patients that have the antibodies.

1216
01:12:25.016 --> 01:12:28.156
This is from the tumor of the patient who has the highest titer of the antibodies.

1217
01:12:28.956 --> 01:12:32.536
So we built a system to try and understand

